04694nam a22006255i 9780804773805DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047738057 a10.1515/97808047738052doi  a(DE-B1597)564538  a(OCoLC)1198930609  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aUA770b.A57 2010 7aPOL0350002bisacsh04a355.07a355/.071 aAdamsky, Dima, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Culture of Military Innovation :bThe Impact of Cultural Factors on the Revolution in Military Affairs in Russia, the US, and Israel. /cDima Adamsky. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. COGNITIVE STYLES AND UNDERSTANDING REVOLUTIONS IN MILITARY AFFAIRS -- t2. THE IMPACT OF CULTURAL FACTORS ON THE SOVIET MILITARY- TECHNICAL REVOLUTION -- t3. THE IMPACT OF CULTURAL FACTORS ON THE US REVOLUTION IN MILITARY AFFAIRS -- t4. THE IMPACT OF CULTURAL FACTORS ON THE ISRAELI REVOLUTION IN MILITARY AFFAIRS -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book studies the impact of cultural factors on the course of military innovations. One would expect that countries accustomed to similar technologies would undergo analogous changes in their perception of and approach to warfare. However, the intellectual history of the Revolution in Military Affairs (RMA) in Russia, the US, and Israel indicates the opposite. The US developed technology and weaponry for about a decade without reconceptualizing the existing paradigm about the nature of warfare. Soviet 'new theory of victory' represented a conceptualization which chronologically preceded technological procurement. Israel was the first to utilize the weaponry on the battlefield, but was the last to develop a conceptual framework that acknowledged its revolutionary implications. Utilizing primary sources that had previously been completely inaccessible, and borrowing methods of analysis from political science, history, anthropology, and cognitive psychology, this book suggests a cultural explanation for this puzzling transformation in warfare. The Culture of Military Innovation offers a systematic, thorough, and unique analytical approach that may well be applicable in other perplexing strategic situations. Though framed in the context of specific historical experience, the insights of this book reveal important implications related to conventional, subconventional, and nonconventional security issues. It is therefore an ideal reference work for practitioners, scholars, teachers, and students of security studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationsxIsrael. 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationsxSoviet Union. 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationsxUnited States. 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationszIsrael. 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationszSoviet Union. 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationszUnited States. 0aStrategic culturexIsrael. 0aStrategic culturexSoviet Union. 0aStrategic culturexUnited States. 0aStrategic culturezIsrael. 0aStrategic culturezSoviet Union. 0aStrategic culturezUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Freedom.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477380540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804773805423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804773805.jpg  a978-3